          "body": "Verse 7 marks the transition from military breach to judicial consequence with a single word: 'It is fixed' (*natsav*, established, decreed). The passive voice carries the weight of divine decision — not a fortune of war but a settled verdict from heaven. 'She is stripped, she is carried away' — the exile-vocabulary (*galah*) is the same word used throughout the prophets for Israel's own deportation. Nineveh tastes what it administered. The handmaids moan like doves and beat their breasts — a vivid image of mourning women, the empire's domestic intimacy shattered in public grief.\n\nVerse 8 delivers the pool-metaphor: 'Though Nineveh was like a pool of water throughout her days, now they are fleeing.' The pool does not empty in violence but in drainage — the people stream away as water finding a hole. 'Stop! Stop!' the officers cry, but no one turns back. The image captures something true about collapsing empires: loyalty evaporates faster than walls fall. Verse 9 turns the camera to the victors: 'Plunder the silver! Plunder the gold!' — the looter's command issued to armies overwhelmed by Nineveh's legendary wealth. 'For there is no limit to the treasure' — the irony is crushing. Nineveh's wealth, gathered by a century of conquest from a dozen nations, is now redistributed in a day."
